pwhm: only rewrite a station's static datamodel info when it changes

wld (the prplMesh WiFi HAL daemon) publishes every associated station under
WiFi.AccessPoint.{i}.AssociatedDevice.{i}. in the datamodel. On each
getStationStats poll from the controller/agent, wld_ad_syncInfo() rewrote the
entire static identity/capability block for that station -- MAC address,
operating standard, supported/negotiated rates, spatial streams, bandwidth and
MLO info, about 40 parameters -- through the ambiorix datamodel transaction
layer (amxd_trans_apply: per-parameter key hashing, hashtable walks, variant
build/free).

That block is constant after association, but it was rewritten on every poll
because the gate keyed on "a fresh driver stats sample arrived" instead of "the
static info actually changed". The driver sample is refreshed every poll, so the
costly write-back fired once per station per poll. The cost grows with the number
of stations per radio and is independent of traffic.

Rewrite the static block only when it can really change -- the first sync after
association, or an association-state change -- and advance the "already synced"
watermark on the skip path so the state-change trigger keeps edge-triggering. The
genuinely time-varying fields (signal strength, last/max data rates) are already
refreshed every poll by the cheap, transaction-free wld_ad_syncStats() path, so
nothing user-visible goes stale.

Measured on a 6-radio reference board at 114 associated stations (perf, 3x 60 s
windows, same image before vs after):

  - datamodel write-transactions committed by wld: ~98/s -> ~3.5/s
    (from ~one per station per poll down to ~one per poll in total)
  - wld CPU: ~44% -> ~28.5% of one core (-15.5 points, ~35% lower)
  - in the CPU profile the static write-back path
    (wld_ad_syncInfo -> amxd_trans_apply) drops from ~22-25% of wld CPU to ~0.5%

The getStationStats call rate, every AssociatedDevice field and association/
disassociation handling are unchanged; a newly associated station still gets its
full static info within a poll or two, and disassociation still clears it. The
remaining per-poll cost is the datamodel read-back that builds the RPC reply,
addressed separately.

Upstream-Status: Pending

diff --git a/src/wld_assocdev.c b/src/wld_assocdev.c
--- a/src/wld_assocdev.c
+++ b/src/wld_assocdev.c
@@ -1926,7 +1926,15 @@
 
     amxd_object_t* afStaTemplateObject = amxd_object_get(object, "AffiliatedSta");
 
-    if(swl_timespec_isZero(&pAD->lastSampleTime) || (swl_timespec_diff(NULL, &pAD->lastSampleSyncTime, &pAD->lastSampleTime) != 0)
+    /* PPW-XXXX: (re)write the static identity/capability block only when it
+     * actually changes -- first sync (A) or an association-state change (C) --
+     * NOT on every driver sample. The dropped per-sample clause
+     * (lastSampleSyncTime != lastSampleTime) fired ~once/poll/station and ran
+     * the full per-station DM write-transaction even though MAC/Caps/rates are
+     * static after assoc. The genuinely-volatile fields (AvgSignalStrength,
+     * Up/DownlinkRateSpec, MaxDownlinkRateReached) are already refreshed every
+     * poll by wld_ad_syncStats() on the cheap, non-transactional path. */
+    if(swl_timespec_isZero(&pAD->lastSampleTime)
        || (pAD->latestStateChangeTime >= pAD->lastSampleSyncTime.tv_sec)) {
         hasData = true;
         SAH_TRACEZ_INFO(ME, "setting info of sta mac %s", pAD->Name);
@@ -2052,6 +2060,10 @@
     }
 
     if(!hasData) {
+        /* PPW-XXXX: advance the watermark even when we skip the write-back, so
+         * the state-change clause edge-triggers. Without this the first state
+         * change would latch clause C true on every subsequent poll. */
+        pAD->lastSampleSyncTime = pAD->lastSampleTime;
         amxd_trans_clean(&trans);
         return SWL_RC_CONTINUE;
     }
